Pioneering Benin funk and soul musician Th√©ophile Do-Rego, known to most as ‚ÄúEl Rego,‚Äù was born on May 3, 1936 in Porto-Novo, Dahomey. He began his career in music in Burkina Faso as a member of the L‚ÄôHarmonie Voltaique orchestra. After returning to Dahomey (now Benin) in 1961, Rego formed his first band, La Filda, and then formed his definitive unit, the Commandos, five years later in 1966. Drawing on hard R&B, soul, and funk, Rego & the Commandos blended these American forms with rumba trappings, Latin percussion, wah-wah guitar, a whole lot of wild accordion, thick basslines, and traditional tribal rhythms to form the musical template that many African bands would follow in ensuing years. In all, Rego and his bands produced some eight SPs (a 7‚Äù format), four LPs, four cassette tape albums, and five CDs, and of course played countless dances, concerts, and clubs during a 50-year run. In 2011 Daptone Records released El Rego, which collected a dozen of Rego's best 45s from the mid-'60s to the early '70s, as selected by Afro-soul collector and DJ Frank Gossner. ~ Steve Leggett, Rovi

Back in 2017, Pop Rap/ Hip-Hop artist Darren Rita began releasing music over on SoundCloud. After releasing two full amateur projects for free, he began taking the craft much more seriously. His early singles built a buzz up around his steadily growing fan base and he capitalized off the momentum by releasing his first full project across all platforms in August of 2019, titled Hysteria. In 2020, he released 20 total tracks which included his fourth full project, Haze. To end the year he ended up releasing a single a week for nine consecutive weeks, which included fan favorites like Youtthetype and Rain on Tuesday. This was followed by another weekly release roll-out in 2021 where he dropped for ten weeks straight. Among the releases were popular tracks Let U Down, Petrified, and Royalty. Inspired by artists like Childish Gambino, Drake, Mike Posner, and many others, Darren has taken many musical endeavors into a variety of different sounds. His versatility as an artist makes it easy to listen to punk rock inspired joints like Afraid of Dying Alone, fresh neo soul songs like Best Me, or inspiring modern hip-hop tunes like 110, in one sitting without feeling out of place. Through his consistency he has been able to push his music to new heights. Whether it's through his music, podcast, or other media ventures, he has consistently been improving with each release and has had a prominent message about the importance of being your true self.

In 2018 the group delivered their debut album 1¬π¬π=1 (Power of Destiny) before disbanding just a year later. Seong Wu embarked on his solo career that year, delivering his debut single, the Flowblow-produced Heart Sign. An obscure all-girl '60ss garage band from Nashville, Tennessee, the Feminine Complex comprised singer/guitarist Mindy Dalton, bassist Jean Williams, vocalist/tambourine player Judi Griffith, organist Pame Stephens, and drummer Lana Napier. The group was formed by Williams and Napier in 1966 while both were sophomores at Nashville's Maplewood High School. Originally named the Pivots, a moniker suggested by the girls' basketball coach, they made their debut at a school talent show -- after recruiting teammates Dalton and Griffith -- dressed in matching pantsuits and performing covers of contemporary hits. After adding Stephens, the quintet rechristened themselves the Feminine Complex and began making regular appearances at Skateland, then Nashville's hottest summer teen hangout. In a local scene otherwise dominated by male combos like the Anglo Saxons, the Feminine Complex quickly earned a cult following, and soon they were touring throughout Tennessee. They caught the attention of A&R vet Dee Kilpatrick, who'd just formed the Athena Records label. The Feminine Complex was the label's first signing, and in 1969, the band's debut LP Livin' Love was released. However, by the time the album appeared the group had already disintegrated -- Stephens, who'd graduated high school, ultimately chose college over rock & roll, and both Williams and Napier quit soon after. Dalton and Griffith briefly forged on as a duo, but by late 1969, the Feminine Complex was no more. In 1996, the hip indie label TeenBeat reissued Livin' Love, followed a year later by the rarities collection To Be in Love. ~ Jason Ankeny, Rovi
